      "writtenOn": "2019-11-05T15:12:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So you want to get EPIPE instead of getting signalled?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2877,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 2881,
        "endChar": 42
      },
      "revId": "b4e0f04e2de9a6aeffd86bcf86e2989a3465384e",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8154a98f_a298eaa5",
        "filename": "libminijail.c",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 2881,
      "author": {
        "id": 1566087
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-05T22:23:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Mostly, I don\u0027t want the current process to be killed if it cannot write into the pipe. Because if the current process is killed, it\u0027s the end of the game.\n\nMy understanding is that setting this signal handler has a global effect on the whole process. I don\u0027t know how this temporary signal handler will interact with other threads, especially if other threads are setting signal handlers at the same time or expecting a SIGPIPE. \n\nSee also https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41190163/disable-sigpipe-signal-on-write2-call-in-library",
      "parentUuid": "81ef52ab_9d26d13e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2877,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 2881,
        "endChar": 42
      },
      "revId": "b4e0f04e2de9a6aeffd86bcf86e2989a3465384e",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f889dd62_b4a1df66",
        "filename": "libminijail.c",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 2881,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-06T15:04:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Signal dispositions are a per-process setting, and not per-thread. And technically libminijail can be embedded in any process, including multi-threaded ones.\n\nBut at the same time, it\u0027s probably more important to not fail catastrophically when there\u0027s a small delay in the child process, so this is fine. If we find errors with blocking SIGPIPE in the future, we can revisit.\n\nI\u0027d only ask to add a comment here saying something like:\n\n\"\n/*\n * Set SIGPIPE handler to SIG_IGN to avoid getting killed by SIGPIPE if the\n * child takes too long to set up its end of the pipe.\n */",
      "parentUuid": "8154a98f_a298eaa5",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2877,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 2881,
        "endChar": 42
      },
      "revId": "b4e0f04e2de9a6aeffd86bcf86e2989a3465384e",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b2fa267e_5e81b71a",
        "filename": "libminijail.c",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 2881,
      "author": {
        "id": 1566087
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-06T23:58:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Added a comment, and also a TODO referencing a new bug ticket tracking the fact that Minijail is not completely thread-safe at the moment.\n\nIf we plan to make it thread-safe, then we\u0027d better follow the approach described here:\nhttps://riptutorial.com/posix/example/17424/handle-sigpipe-generated-by-write---in-a-thread-safe-manner\nhttp://www.microhowto.info/howto/ignore_sigpipe_without_affecting_other_threads_in_a_process.html\n\nHowever, I couldn\u0027t use pthread_sigmask since Minijail doesn\u0027t seem to be built with pthreads. Instead, I used sigprocmask, but its effect is unspecified in multithreaded programs. I also noticed that other parts of Minijail already use sigprocmask, so the thread safety of Minijail as a whole is already suspicious.",
      "parentUuid": "f889dd62_b4a1df66",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2877,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 2881,
        "endChar": 42
      },
